article.headline: ASU crumbles under Lobos' pressure
article.linkText: New Mexico makes its case with upset of ASU
article.story:
ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- All those turnovers didn't matter. Not
the way New Mexico played defense Saturday against Arizona
State (No. 25 ESPN/USA Today; No. 23 AP).

	   New Mexico overcame 24 turnovers with its tenacious man defense
and aggressive rebounding to beat the Sun Devils 61-45.

	   The Lobos (7-1) snapped ASU's six-game winning streak by holding
the Sun Devils (7-2) to season lows in points and shooting
percentage (29.5 percent).

	   "Our defense was just the equalizer," said New Mexico coach
Don Flanagan of his team's best win of the season. "We wanted to
hold them to 61 and we held them to 45. Our defense wasn't too
shabby."

	   Abbie Letz provided the offensive spark with a season-high 16
points. She hit 6 of 9 shots and was 4-for-5 on 3-pointers. Her
second 3-pointer of the second half gave the Lobos a 44-31 lead
with 12:44 left.

	   ASU cut the deficit to 48-41 on a turnaround jumper by Amy
Denson with 3:36 left, but Judy Vogt banked in a shot for New
Mexico and Mandi Moore hit five free throws over the final 2:13 to
keep the Lobos in control.

	   Arizona State, which came into the game averaging just under 72
points a game, hit just 8 of 33 shots in the second half after
missing 13 of its first 16 in the final 20 minutes.

	   "We were terrible," said ASU coach Charli Turner Thorne. "We
played kind of like it was a practice. We had open looks all days,
but we didn't finish plays. We missed 22 shots in the paint and
that's a lot to overcome in The Pit."

	   "Not to make excuses because I think New Mexico played great,"
Thorne said. "They made some tough shots and did some things that
were really good."

	   ASU had not lost since mid-November, when the Sun Devils fell
65-54 to then No. 3 Louisiana State. They'll have little time to
regroup from the loss to unranked New Mexico since they play No. 8
Connecticut on Tuesday in Tempe.

	   Flanagan, obviously pleased with the way his team defended the
Sun Devils, offered a bold prediction by saying, "I don't think
anyone else will hold them to 45."

	   The Sun Devils were led by Denson with 14 points and Kristen
Kovesdy with 10. Guard Kylan Loney, the team's leading scorer with
13.8 points per game failed to score. She was 0-for-7 from the
field before fouling out with 2:13 left in the game.

	   Moore added 12 points for the Lobos, who also dominated on the
boards behind reserves Dionne Marsh and Jana Francis. New Mexico
had a 40-22 edge in rebounding, with the 6-foot-1 freshman Marsh
and 6-3 Francis each grabbing seven rebounds.

	   New Mexico never trailed after Moore hit a 3-pointer that put
the Lobos ahead 18-15 with 9:12 to go in the first half. The Lobos
hit 13 of 20 shots in the first half to take a 32-27 lead. Letz's
shooting in the second half and the defense more than made up for
the Lobos' less-than-solid 39 percent shooting in the second half.
